{{Short description|Shinto Shrine to the Sea God Watatsumi located in Kobe Japan}}
{{Draft topics|east-asia}}
{{AfC topic|geo}}
{{AfC submission|||ts=20230406182155|u=Immanuelle|ns=118}}
{{draft}}
{{Infobox Shinto shrine
| name                  = Watatsumi Jinja
| religious_affiliation = Shinto
| image                 = Kobe-wtatumijinjya35.JPG
}}
{{Interlanguage link|Watatsumi jinja|ja|海神社 (神戸市)|link=|prefix=|foreign=}} is a [[Shinto shrine]] located in [[Japan]]. It was founded by [[Empress Jingu]] when she returned from the Three Han (三韓, Korea) campaign.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |title=Shinto shrines {{!}} Japan {{!}} Rods Shinto |url=https://www.rodsshinto.com/ |access-date=2023-04-04 |website=shintoshrines |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web |title=Watatsumi Shrine {{!}} 海神社 {{!}}Hyogo-ken, Kobe-shi |url=https://www.rodsshinto.com/28-108-01 |access-date=2023-04-06 |website=shintoshrines |language=en}}</ref>

She was nearly shipwrecked but managed to survive thanks to praying to [[Watatsumi]], and she made the shrine to honor him.<ref name=":1" /> [[Ikasuri Shrine]] and [[Ikuta Shrine]] were both also made at the same time by the Empress.<ref name=":1" />

It is colloquially called {{Nihongo|Sea Shrine|海神社|Umi Jinja}} due to that being a more common reading of the characters<ref name=":1" />

== History ==
It was first mentioned in 806<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" />

In the [[Edo Period]] it was considered highly significant to the rulers of the [[Akashi Domain]] and the rulers visited it every February.<ref name=":1" />

Originally its main [[Torii]] was located on the beach, but due to land reclamation after [[WWII]] its torii is now a fair bit inland<ref name=":1" />

== See Also ==

* [[Draft:Kaijin Shrine|Kaijin Shrine]] which is sometimes also known as "Watatsumi Jinja"

