{{Interlanguage link|Watatsumi Shrine|ja|海神社 (神戸市)|simple|link=|prefix=|foreign=}} is a [[Shinto shrine]] located in [[Japan]]. It was founded by [[Empress Jingu]] when she returned from the Three Han (三韓, Korea) campaign.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |title=Shinto shrines {{!}} Japan {{!}} Rods Shinto |url=https://www.rodsshinto.com/ |access-date=2023-04-04 |website=shintoshrines |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web |title=Watatsumi Shrine {{!}} 海神社 {{!}}Hyogo-ken, Kobe-shi |url=https://www.rodsshinto.com/28-108-01 |access-date=2023-04-06 |website=shintoshrines |language=en}}</ref>

She was nearly shipwrecked but managed to survive thanks to praying to [[Watatsumi]], and she made the shrine to honor him.<ref name=":1" /> [[Ikasuri Shrine]] and [[Ikuta Shrine]] were both also made at the same time by the Empress.<ref name=":1" />

It is colloquially called {{Nihongo|Sea Shrine|海神社|Umi Jinja}} due to that being a more common reading of the characters<ref name=":1" />


Tomomi no Sukune's first son Tairyo became the first priest of the shrine.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Ponsonby-Fane |first=R. A. B. |url=https://www.amazon.ca/Studies-Shinto-Shrines-R-Ponsonby-Fane/dp/1138983225 |title=Studies In Shinto & Shrines |date=2016-05-11 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-138-98322-9 |edition=1st edition |pages=335 |language=English}}</ref>

== History ==
It was first mentioned in 806<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" />

In the [[Edo Period]] it was considered highly significant to the rulers of the [[Akashi Domain]] and the rulers visited it every February.<ref name=":1" />

Originally its main [[Torii]] was located on the beach, but due to land reclamation after [[WWII]] its torii is now a fair bit inland<ref name=":1" />

