'''Watatsumi Shrine''' (海神社, Watatsumi Jinja)  is a [[Shinto shrine]] located in [[Kobe]]. It was founded by [[Empress Jingu]] when she returned from the Three Han (三韓, Korea) campaign.<ref name="shintoshrines-2023a">{{Cite web |title=Shinto shrines {{!}} Japan {{!}} Rods Shinto |url=https://www.rodsshinto.com/ |access-date=2023-04-04 |website=shintoshrines |language=en}}</ref><ref name="shintoshrines-2023b">{{Cite web |title=Watatsumi Shrine {{!}} 海神社 {{!}}Hyogo-ken, Kobe-shi |url=https://www.rodsshinto.com/28-108-01 |access-date=2023-04-06 |website=shintoshrines |language=en}}</ref> <ref name=":0">{{Cite web |title=The Romance of Kobe |url=https://www.forgottenbooks.com/en/readbook/TheRomanceofKobe_10127101#12 |access-date=2023-11-24 |website=www.forgottenbooks.com}}</ref>{{rp|7}}

There are 22 Watatsumi shrines in the region that claim to have been founded by her in these circumstances. <ref name=":0" />{{rp|7}} 


It is a [[Myojin Taisha]] in the [[Engishiki]].<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QmdRAAAAYAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=Watatsumi+Shrine&q=Watatsumi+Shrine&hl=en |title=Engi-shiki; Procedures of the Engi Era: Books VI-X |date=1972 |publisher=Sophia University |language=en}}</ref>

She was nearly shipwrecked but managed to survive thanks to praying to [[Watatsumi]], and she made the shrine to honor him. <ref name=":0" />{{rp|7}}.<ref name="shintoshrines-2023b" /> [[Ikasuri Shrine]] and [[Ikuta Shrine]] were both also made at the same time by the Empress.<ref name="shintoshrines-2023b" />

It is colloquially called {{Nihongo|Sea Shrine|海神社|Umi Jinja}} due to that being a more common reading of the characters<ref name="shintoshrines-2023b" />. It is also read as Kai Shrine or called Tarumi Shrine <ref name=":0" />{{rp|7}}

It is one of the three major shrines of [[Harima Province]].<ref name="shintoshrines-2023b" />
Tomomi no Sukune's first son Tairyo became the first priest of the shrine.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Ponsonby-Fane |first=R. A. B. |title=Studies In Shinto & Shrines |date=2016-05-11 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-138-98322-9 |edition=1st |pages=335 |language=English}}</ref>

It has a festival on October 11.<ref name="shintoshrines-2023b" />

== History ==
It was first mentioned in 806<ref name="shintoshrines-2023a" /><ref name="shintoshrines-2023b" />

In the [[Edo Period]] it was considered highly significant to the rulers of the [[Akashi Domain]] and the rulers visited it every February.<ref name="shintoshrines-2023b" />

Originally its main [[Torii]] was located on the beach, but due to land reclamation after [[WWII]] its torii is now a fair bit inland<ref name="shintoshrines-2023b" />
